1
00:00:08,080 --> 00:00:09,400
Have you ever wondered

2
00:00:09,440 --> 00:00:12,560
how different our lives would be

3
00:00:12,840 --> 00:00:14,840
if goodness could be redeemed for wishes?

4
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:16,480
It's gotta be money,

5
00:00:16,960 --> 00:00:18,200
work,

6
00:00:18,520 --> 00:00:19,680
or a lover!

7
00:00:24,680 --> 00:00:27,360
Is this the wish I received?

8
00:00:27,640 --> 00:00:33,840
This series explores the idea,
"What if we could collect merit points

9
00:00:33,880 --> 00:00:36,320
and use them to redeem wishes?"

10
00:00:36,360 --> 00:00:39,520
This is the core idea of the series.
[Pannares Ruchirananta, Director]

11
00:00:40,040 --> 00:00:44,600
Wishes can be redeemed
through an app called "Lucky Points."

12
00:00:44,640 --> 00:00:46,480
[Spending merit points via the Lucky Points app]

13
00:00:46,680 --> 00:00:48,480
Baipor plays Jane.
[Niwirin Limkangwalmongkol as Z]

14
00:00:49,040 --> 00:00:51,120
Yes, she's a Gen Z girl.

15
00:00:51,160 --> 00:00:52,920
As for me, I play Z,
[Thitiya Jirapornsilp as Jane]

16
00:00:52,960 --> 00:00:57,160
an angel who can do nothing at all.

17
00:00:57,200 --> 00:00:59,220
How did both of us cross paths?

18
00:00:59,260 --> 00:01:06,240
The setup of the series
involves an app called Lucky Points.

19
00:01:06,280 --> 00:01:12,320
Since Jane is an ambitious teenage girl,

20
00:01:12,360 --> 00:01:18,039
she uses the app to redeem a wish.

21
00:01:18,080 --> 00:01:25,680
She ends up with a hot angel

22
00:01:25,720 --> 00:01:27,880
who can do nothing.

23
00:01:27,920 --> 00:01:29,340
She complimented me!
[Just a little compliment is enough, right?]

24
00:01:29,380 --> 00:01:30,720
She complimented Z!

25
00:01:30,760 --> 00:01:33,160
I came into existence to do her bidding.

26
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:35,720
For example,
if she wants me to do the dishes,

27
00:01:35,759 --> 00:01:37,000
I have to do it.

28
00:01:37,039 --> 00:01:38,440
But I might only clean the top,

29
00:01:38,700 --> 00:01:40,520
- not the bottom of the dishes.
- So...

30
00:01:40,560 --> 00:01:42,680
- That's how things go.
- You're basically my minion.

31
00:01:42,720 --> 00:01:44,680
- Yes.
- Z is Jane's minion.

32
00:01:44,720 --> 00:01:46,960
Yes, I'll do anything to make her happy.

33
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:49,560
I'm not sure if she would, though.

34
00:01:49,600 --> 00:01:52,720
The angel who is supposed to assist her
instead becomes her burden.

35
00:01:52,759 --> 00:01:55,360
Rather than helping her,
the angel can do nothing.

36
00:01:55,940 --> 00:02:00,040
Since they'll be together for 3 months,

37
00:02:00,080 --> 00:02:03,040
she wants to find out
who the angel really is.

38
00:02:03,080 --> 00:02:04,920
This might at least be useful in some ways.

39
00:02:04,960 --> 00:02:09,190
So Jane decides to use the theory
"six degrees of separation,"

40
00:02:09,229 --> 00:02:10,840
also known as
the small-world phenomenon.

41
00:02:10,880 --> 00:02:18,760
This series primarily follows
2 main characters

42
00:02:18,800 --> 00:02:21,520
as they meet different people

43
00:02:21,560 --> 00:02:23,200
and complete the tasks in each EP.

44
00:02:23,240 --> 00:02:25,960
That's where the fun of the series lies.

45
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:27,800
Your mission is...

46
00:02:27,840 --> 00:02:31,040
You have to sleep in a room with a dark history.

47
00:02:33,840 --> 00:02:35,840
(Chanting)

48
00:02:35,880 --> 00:02:39,200
From now on, I'm just someone
who will be by your side

49
00:02:39,240 --> 00:02:41,240
for three months, Jane.

50
00:02:43,240 --> 00:02:47,120
Heaven, why are you sending
an angel like this to me?

51
00:02:47,160 --> 00:02:48,600
[When getting stuck with "a useless angel,"

52
00:02:48,640 --> 00:02:50,630
the mission to find one's identity has now begun]

53
00:02:50,840 --> 00:02:54,110
To start with,
I've always enjoyed coming up with

54
00:02:54,150 --> 00:02:56,360
and writing stories every day.

55
00:02:56,680 --> 00:03:00,960
So I have a lot of different ideas saved,

56
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:02,390
including the plot of this series,

57
00:03:02,420 --> 00:03:05,200
which I wrote after the pandemic.

58
00:03:05,240 --> 00:03:07,640
However,
this is the most detailed work I've written.

59
00:03:08,400 --> 00:03:10,760
I even came up with the settings.

60
00:03:10,800 --> 00:03:13,760
Before I passed it to my team,
I already had a rough outline

61
00:03:13,800 --> 00:03:17,800
of what would happen in each EP.

62
00:03:17,840 --> 00:03:21,000
It's fairly detailed
and can be visualized to a certain degree.

63
00:03:21,280 --> 00:03:24,480
Then, out of the blue,
I wanted this series to come to life.

64
00:03:24,520 --> 00:03:27,680
One day, I went on a trip with Fern,

65
00:03:27,720 --> 00:03:32,079
and I told her, "I wanna produce this series.
I still wanna do it."

66
00:03:32,120 --> 00:03:35,440
Then she told me to
explain everything in great detail,

67
00:03:35,480 --> 00:03:37,920
as if I were pitching a project to a client.

68
00:03:37,960 --> 00:03:39,400
And I did just that.

69
00:03:39,440 --> 00:03:42,800
I didn't expect that I'd be pitching
a project to my wife.

70
00:03:42,840 --> 00:03:45,680
She randomly told me about the project.
[Rongwalai Muansawad, Executive Producer]

71
00:03:45,720 --> 00:03:48,040
She already had her own core idea.
[Apiwan Jantapa, Executive Producer]

72
00:03:48,079 --> 00:03:50,440
She explained everything to me in detail.

73
00:03:50,640 --> 00:03:55,560
As I was listening to her pitch,
I liked her idea.

74
00:03:55,760 --> 00:03:57,760
So I told her, "Let's do this."

75
00:03:57,800 --> 00:03:59,220
Then, the first person who came to mind

76
00:03:59,680 --> 00:04:01,020
[Someone she wants to work with]

77
00:04:01,060 --> 00:04:02,160
was this lovely lady.

78
00:04:02,200 --> 00:04:06,360
She called me and asked if we could meet,

79
00:04:06,400 --> 00:04:10,600
and we talked.
I saw both of their dedication

80
00:04:10,640 --> 00:04:12,760
and how much they really wanted
this project to come to life.

81
00:04:12,800 --> 00:04:14,560
Then, we had another meeting.

82
00:04:14,600 --> 00:04:19,440
Poy, the director, gave me a synopsis.

83
00:04:19,480 --> 00:04:20,970
After reading through it

84
00:04:21,010 --> 00:04:22,520
and seeing that

85
00:04:22,560 --> 00:04:25,160
one of the main cast members is Baipor,

86
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:26,600
whom Fern has been mentoring

87
00:04:26,640 --> 00:04:29,880
and paving the way for,

88
00:04:29,920 --> 00:04:32,230
it became clear
that she had a lot of faith in Baipor

89
00:04:32,270 --> 00:04:34,600
to have her play a role in a GL series.

90
00:04:34,640 --> 00:04:37,480
It's a departure from
the characters she played.

91
00:04:37,520 --> 00:04:40,680
When it was revealed that
Bambam would be her partner,

92
00:04:40,720 --> 00:04:42,080
I immediately felt their chemistry,

93
00:04:42,120 --> 00:04:49,240
and I believe this pairing
will warm everyone's hearts.

94
00:04:51,880 --> 00:04:54,960
As I've said,
I came up with this project myself.

95
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:59,200
Then I wrote the long-form synopsis.

96
00:04:59,240 --> 00:05:02,480
I also created characters for Jane and Z.

97
00:05:02,520 --> 00:05:04,200
I was able to provide the team

98
00:05:04,240 --> 00:05:06,840
with a wide range of materials,

99
00:05:06,880 --> 00:05:09,580
such as an outline describing the events

100
00:05:09,620 --> 00:05:11,920
that would take place in each EP

101
00:05:11,960 --> 00:05:13,720
and what I wanted to see in them.

102
00:05:13,760 --> 00:05:16,720
I went into great details
and explained it to Pang.

103
00:05:16,760 --> 00:05:18,760
It took me 4 hours to do just that.
[Sharing details with the screenwriters]

104
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:19,800
I think that really confused her.

105
00:05:19,840 --> 00:05:23,000
I explained everything
as if I were an insurance salesperson.

106
00:05:23,040 --> 00:05:25,520
I was shocked when I got the materials,
[Hempiran Pindhusenee, Screenwriter]

107
00:05:25,740 --> 00:05:27,040
as I'm not comedic by nature.
[Chanikarn O. Lee, Screenwriter]

108
00:05:27,880 --> 00:05:30,040
- And neither is she.
- Neither am I.

109
00:05:30,080 --> 00:05:31,400
Deep down, we are,

110
00:05:31,440 --> 00:05:33,740
but we needed help with this rom-com series.

111
00:05:35,200 --> 00:05:38,040
Fortunately, our director is quite funny.

112
00:05:38,440 --> 00:05:41,280
- So we took a few pages from her playbook
- Yeah.

113
00:05:41,320 --> 00:05:44,440
and injected them into the series.

114
00:05:44,640 --> 00:05:48,360
The first time I heard about the project,

115
00:05:48,860 --> 00:05:49,920
I found it to be pretty sweet.

116
00:05:49,960 --> 00:05:53,280
With Baipor at the forefront,
the whole picture became clear to me,

117
00:05:53,320 --> 00:05:56,320
and I felt she would be
a lovely addition to the project.

118
00:05:56,360 --> 00:06:00,850
That's why I think the series
might surprise everyone,

119
00:06:00,890 --> 00:06:04,280
as Baipor usually plays serious characters.

120
00:06:04,320 --> 00:06:09,040
Poy has directed several GL series herself.

121
00:06:09,080 --> 00:06:13,960
Since Poy and I are both butch,

122
00:06:14,200 --> 00:06:17,740
we want the pairing to be a butch character
and a femme character.

123
00:06:17,780 --> 00:06:21,040
I want the character to reflect who we are.
[Wanting to tell butch-femme stories]

124
00:06:21,080 --> 00:06:25,280
It was clear from our meeting
that we wanted to make a sapphic series.

125
00:06:25,560 --> 00:06:29,160
Sapphic series are my cup of tea.

126
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:30,830
We sat down and talked it through.

127
00:06:30,870 --> 00:06:32,870
Then we decided to go back to the start.

128
00:06:33,280 --> 00:06:37,120
I wanted a butch-femme pairing.

129
00:06:37,360 --> 00:06:41,040
As for the genre of this series,

130
00:06:41,080 --> 00:06:44,200
it's sapphic romance, comedy, and fantasy.

131
00:06:44,240 --> 00:06:47,120
It's gonna be euphoric,
wholesome, and heartwarming.

132
00:06:47,159 --> 00:06:48,320
Let's talk about the rom-com aspect.

133
00:06:48,550 --> 00:06:52,360
Rom-com was my favorite genre
back when I was a film student.

134
00:06:52,480 --> 00:06:54,870
So a rom-com would be the kind of series

135
00:06:54,909 --> 00:06:57,320
I'd want to produce if I had the chance.

136
00:06:57,360 --> 00:06:59,320
A cookie-cutter rom-com series
is fine by me.

137
00:06:59,360 --> 00:07:04,280
As for the fantasy aspect,
I'm a fan of heavily fantasy-driven films.

138
00:07:04,320 --> 00:07:06,470
That's why I'm merging the two genres.

139
00:07:06,510 --> 00:07:08,380
The first thing we did
was lay the groundwork

140
00:07:08,420 --> 00:07:10,190
- for the app Lucky Points.
- Lucky Points.

141
00:07:10,230 --> 00:07:12,430
Poy and I spent a long time
planning everything out,

142
00:07:13,030 --> 00:07:15,200
like who redeemed the wish

143
00:07:15,240 --> 00:07:17,800
and how an angel came to be.

144
00:07:17,840 --> 00:07:21,680
The most challenging part was the app.

145
00:07:21,720 --> 00:07:27,240
When nothing was settled,
the plot kept pivoting from one place to another.

146
00:07:27,880 --> 00:07:30,880
Once the app was done,
it was smooth sailing.

147
00:07:30,920 --> 00:07:34,880
I've heard too much about
the term "merit points" in Thailand.

148
00:07:34,920 --> 00:07:37,070
When something comes true,
one would say,

149
00:07:37,110 --> 00:07:38,560
"Oh, I have merit points,"

150
00:07:38,600 --> 00:07:40,080
and if it doesn't,
"I don't have merit points."

151
00:07:40,120 --> 00:07:41,440
The concept interested me.

152
00:07:41,480 --> 00:07:45,480
In real life, we have to guess
if we have enough so-called merit points.

153
00:07:45,520 --> 00:07:48,440
And what would happen
if we had control over them?

154
00:07:48,480 --> 00:07:50,360
That's the question I came up with.

155
00:07:50,400 --> 00:07:54,480
[Do you think you have a lot of merit points?]

156
00:07:54,800 --> 00:07:56,120
I think I do.

157
00:07:56,560 --> 00:07:58,960
I've made a lot of merit.

158
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:01,280
I like the act of doing good deeds.

159
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:03,880
Gosh, now this is gonna be
hard for me to answer.

160
00:08:03,920 --> 00:08:06,760
I also think I'm someone
with a lot of merit points.

161
00:08:07,160 --> 00:08:09,080
I always tell everyone,

162
00:08:09,660 --> 00:08:11,280
"I feel like I've got a lot of merit points,

163
00:08:11,320 --> 00:08:12,990
and I don't know when I'll run out."

164
00:08:13,200 --> 00:08:18,720
Things seem to come into my life effortlessly.

165
00:08:18,760 --> 00:08:20,320
- Just like that.
- You're a lucky person.

166
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:23,520
Still, I think I should do more good deeds.

167
00:08:23,720 --> 00:08:25,520
I've used up so many points.

168
00:08:25,680 --> 00:08:26,640
Something like that.

169
00:08:26,680 --> 00:08:30,000
[Out of 100, how many do you think you've got?]

170
00:08:30,040 --> 00:08:31,240
I would say 70.

171
00:08:31,880 --> 00:08:35,960
Honestly,
I don't think mine's higher than 70.

172
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:39,120
But I do think it's quite high.

173
00:08:39,159 --> 00:08:41,000
We both have a lot of merit points.

174
00:08:41,039 --> 00:08:42,220
Sadhu!

175
00:08:42,919 --> 00:08:43,799
Please!

176
00:08:44,520 --> 00:08:47,040
Luck doesn't favor you.

177
00:08:48,280 --> 00:08:50,600
Usually, when I create a character,

178
00:08:50,640 --> 00:08:55,640
I'd leave it at around 60-70%.

179
00:08:55,840 --> 00:08:57,040
It's just the husk.

180
00:08:57,080 --> 00:09:00,520
However, it paints
a general idea of who would fit the character.

181
00:09:00,560 --> 00:09:03,320
Once we realized
we wanted a butch-femme pair,

182
00:09:03,360 --> 00:09:08,800
I started listing
every butch actor I could think of.

183
00:09:08,980 --> 00:09:09,960
So I made a list.

184
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:11,160
It felt like destiny.

185
00:09:11,200 --> 00:09:12,400
Here's an anecdote.

186
00:09:12,660 --> 00:09:14,320
I was driving,

187
00:09:14,360 --> 00:09:18,760
and 'ROCKET,' a song by Bambam,
started playing.

188
00:09:18,940 --> 00:09:21,960
Then it hit me:
"Hey! How did I forget about her?!

189
00:09:22,400 --> 00:09:24,440
She might be able to play Z."

190
00:09:24,480 --> 00:09:28,680
The character I designed for Z
is a sweet, gentle soul

191
00:09:29,160 --> 00:09:32,240
who is very charismatic.

192
00:09:32,280 --> 00:09:33,520
And she has the charisma.

193
00:09:33,560 --> 00:09:35,520
When I contacted her

194
00:09:35,560 --> 00:09:37,320
and met her,

195
00:09:37,360 --> 00:09:40,480
I felt like she had
something in common with Z.

196
00:09:40,520 --> 00:09:45,600
I was then able to tie her
to the character I had in mind.

197
00:09:45,640 --> 00:09:47,000
That's why we went with Bambam.

198
00:09:47,040 --> 00:09:49,840
The challenge I have in playing Z...

199
00:09:49,880 --> 00:09:52,360
I have none.

200
00:09:52,400 --> 00:09:53,700
Z is a very easy character for me to play.

201
00:09:53,740 --> 00:09:56,680
She and I share a lot of similarities.

202
00:09:56,720 --> 00:10:00,840
Z is someone
who doesn't get hung up on minor details

203
00:10:00,880 --> 00:10:04,680
and wants to make everyone around her happy.

204
00:10:04,720 --> 00:10:07,080
Say, if something were to upset her,

205
00:10:07,120 --> 00:10:09,080
she'd look at the bright side.

206
00:10:09,120 --> 00:10:11,400
Whenever I'm with the crew or others,

207
00:10:11,440 --> 00:10:13,200
I tend to spend time with them.

208
00:10:13,240 --> 00:10:15,450
Z is the same way.

209
00:10:15,960 --> 00:10:18,240
She simply wants to make
the person by her side happy.

210
00:10:18,280 --> 00:10:20,080
Bambam joined us
before the plot was completed.

211
00:10:20,120 --> 00:10:21,920
So we had already met her
while we were working on it.

212
00:10:21,960 --> 00:10:25,270
During the treatment,
as we looked at the footage and stuff,

213
00:10:25,310 --> 00:10:27,000
we started to get the picture.

214
00:10:27,040 --> 00:10:30,240
Naturally,
we have to keep track of her and stuff.

215
00:10:30,280 --> 00:10:32,120
We did inject a lot of her character
into the writing.

216
00:10:32,160 --> 00:10:36,560
Bambam is a butch who is

217
00:10:36,600 --> 00:10:39,620
- sweet, soft, and pure.
- She's sweet.

218
00:10:39,660 --> 00:10:41,600
In the story, Jane is very strict.

219
00:10:42,120 --> 00:10:43,120
She's like...

220
00:10:43,160 --> 00:10:47,040
That's why we think
her character suits the series.

221
00:10:47,080 --> 00:10:49,920
We can see whether
Bambam would get sad

222
00:10:49,960 --> 00:10:53,840
after being berated by Baipor.

223
00:10:54,080 --> 00:10:57,080
It's like a strict cat and a puppy.

224
00:10:57,120 --> 00:10:57,920
Exactly!

225
00:10:58,240 --> 00:10:59,440
- That's the type of chemistry.
- And that's lovely.

226
00:10:59,480 --> 00:11:02,400
When we saw the pictures, we were like,
"Aww, they're pretty cute."

227
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:04,600
We were like...

228
00:11:04,640 --> 00:11:06,640
"Aww, Bambam is so adorable!"
[Even the screenwriters melted]

229
00:11:07,080 --> 00:11:11,200
[The team says the series is actually called
"Be My Angry," since Jane is pretty strict]

230
00:11:11,440 --> 00:11:12,640
Is Jane strict?

231
00:11:12,680 --> 00:11:14,000
Is she strict?

232
00:11:14,040 --> 00:11:16,260
She's not strict, but she's more like,

233
00:11:16,300 --> 00:11:17,660
"This is how I want it.

234
00:11:17,900 --> 00:11:19,130
You have to do as I say."

235
00:11:19,170 --> 00:11:20,110
Something like that.

236
00:11:20,150 --> 00:11:22,340
She's self-assured, you know?

237
00:11:22,380 --> 00:11:23,620
- Too self-assured.
- That's who she is.

238
00:11:23,660 --> 00:11:25,060
Too much.

239
00:11:25,540 --> 00:11:27,420
Yeah, it's "Be My Angry," right?

240
00:11:27,460 --> 00:11:28,880
- Yeah.
- That's what everybody's been saying.

241
00:11:28,920 --> 00:11:32,760
But there are times when she's nice to me.

242
00:11:33,060 --> 00:11:35,980
In a lot of scenes, Poy would tell me...

243
00:11:36,020 --> 00:11:40,520
"Don't be angry.
Try not to be too angry, okay?"

244
00:11:40,680 --> 00:11:43,020
She got mad at me not just on set,

245
00:11:43,440 --> 00:11:46,840
but off camera in real life too.

246
00:11:46,880 --> 00:11:48,960
She's lying. Don't listen to her, guys.
[Just kidding]

247
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:50,320
She cares about me.

248
00:11:50,840 --> 00:11:53,400
As for Baipor,
we actually knew each other beforehand,

249
00:11:53,440 --> 00:11:55,280
since Fern was taking care of her.

250
00:11:55,320 --> 00:11:58,410
When it came to Jane, I was wondering

251
00:11:58,440 --> 00:12:01,960
who could represent what JaneZ is about.

252
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:04,800
The night I wrote the pilot EP,
I could see Baipor in it.

253
00:12:04,840 --> 00:12:09,760
But the characters
I usually see her play are very dramatic,

254
00:12:09,800 --> 00:12:15,000
so I wondered
if a rom-com series would work for her.

255
00:12:15,040 --> 00:12:19,240
That's when I decided to
have a meeting with her,

256
00:12:19,280 --> 00:12:20,720
asking if she was okay with this.

257
00:12:20,760 --> 00:12:23,080
Then we tried to get her in tune
with the character, and it worked.

258
00:12:23,520 --> 00:12:26,240
So I asked her
if she wanted to work on the series.

259
00:12:26,280 --> 00:12:28,200
"Okay, give me a moment to think."

260
00:12:28,620 --> 00:12:30,320
She sent me that text at 5 P.M.

261
00:12:30,520 --> 00:12:33,280
Then she went to see a movie
and left the cinema around 9 P.M.

262
00:12:33,320 --> 00:12:34,280
Then she texted me, "Okay, I'm down."

263
00:12:34,320 --> 00:12:35,600
[She said yes pretty quickly]

264
00:12:35,640 --> 00:12:36,560
She was very quick.

265
00:12:36,600 --> 00:12:38,920
I didn't think
she'd give me an answer that quickly.

266
00:12:38,960 --> 00:12:40,320
If you ask me,

267
00:12:40,360 --> 00:12:44,040
I believe she has the potential

268
00:12:44,080 --> 00:12:48,280
to shift drama roles to a rom-com.

269
00:12:48,320 --> 00:12:51,120
I also believe
she can convey the message well.

270
00:12:51,160 --> 00:12:54,000
Her character actually has some issues.

271
00:12:54,040 --> 00:12:56,590
She's a layered character,
with emotional baggage,

272
00:12:56,610 --> 00:12:58,040
trauma, sorrow, and more.

273
00:12:58,080 --> 00:13:00,240
You have to stay tuned.
That's all I can say.

274
00:13:00,620 --> 00:13:03,380
It's really hard, actually.

275
00:13:04,500 --> 00:13:11,760
At first, I couldn't really tune in to
the character all day,

276
00:13:11,800 --> 00:13:18,360
since Jane is way more upbeat than I am.

277
00:13:18,400 --> 00:13:22,600
Her daily life moves
at a different pace than mine.

278
00:13:22,640 --> 00:13:26,240
I need to find a way to match her energy

279
00:13:26,280 --> 00:13:28,560
and keep it up all day.

280
00:13:28,800 --> 00:13:29,830
That's the challenge.

281
00:13:29,870 --> 00:13:33,880
Still, once I got to explore the character
throughout the scenes,

282
00:13:33,920 --> 00:13:38,240
these aspects completed the character.

283
00:13:38,280 --> 00:13:42,400
When I got to see
the character's personality and the setting,

284
00:13:42,440 --> 00:13:45,360
I was able to get a clearer picture.

285
00:13:45,400 --> 00:13:48,240
Right from the start,
their chemistry has been...

286
00:13:48,680 --> 00:13:49,880
When they first played a scene together,

287
00:13:49,920 --> 00:13:52,920
Baipor was a bit strict

288
00:13:52,960 --> 00:13:54,720
as that's part of her nature.

289
00:13:54,760 --> 00:13:55,880
She is a quiet person.

290
00:13:55,920 --> 00:13:59,080
At the same time,
if something doesn't go her way,

291
00:13:59,120 --> 00:14:00,840
she'll say it.

292
00:14:00,880 --> 00:14:03,960
Meanwhile, Bambam is soft and gentle.

293
00:14:04,080 --> 00:14:06,520
They're like cats and dogs.

294
00:14:06,560 --> 00:14:08,480
You'll get to see
this kind of dynamic a lot.

295
00:14:08,520 --> 00:14:10,720
In the behind-the-scenes,
you might even get to see them

296
00:14:10,760 --> 00:14:13,200
bantering as if they're really close.

297
00:14:13,240 --> 00:14:17,380
They've been working
and sharing so many moments together

298
00:14:17,420 --> 00:14:20,200
that they talk to each other
more than they do to us.

299
00:14:20,240 --> 00:14:21,880
So we always see them having sweet moments.

300
00:14:21,920 --> 00:14:25,520
- They're being themselves when they're together.
- Being themselves.

301
00:14:25,560 --> 00:14:27,840
When it comes to their chemistry...

302
00:14:27,880 --> 00:14:29,600
Let's go back to before they met.

303
00:14:29,640 --> 00:14:34,480
My plan was not to let them know that
they were each other's partner.

304
00:14:34,520 --> 00:14:36,920
When they first met,
their first impression...

305
00:14:37,080 --> 00:14:38,560
was just

306
00:14:38,600 --> 00:14:40,000
staring at each other.

307
00:14:40,040 --> 00:14:41,960
"Hello. I'm Bambam."

308
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:44,000
"Hi, I'm Baipor." That's it.

309
00:14:44,680 --> 00:14:46,720
- Our first day?
- You sighed?!

310
00:14:46,760 --> 00:14:49,280
I mean, the first day was when I...

311
00:14:50,080 --> 00:14:54,120
My head was in the clouds.

312
00:14:54,280 --> 00:14:56,080
At the time, I wasn't mentally prepared,

313
00:14:56,120 --> 00:14:58,840
and I didn't know who my partner would be.

314
00:14:59,680 --> 00:15:02,680
I opened the door, and there she was.

315
00:15:02,720 --> 00:15:05,200
Deep down, I was actually nervous,

316
00:15:05,240 --> 00:15:06,820
and I didn't know how to act.

317
00:15:06,860 --> 00:15:08,120
I was listening to Poy,

318
00:15:08,160 --> 00:15:09,960
but at the same time
I was lost in my thoughts.

319
00:15:10,400 --> 00:15:11,520
What about you, Baipor?

320
00:15:11,760 --> 00:15:12,960
- On that day?
- Yeah.

321
00:15:13,360 --> 00:15:14,560
I felt like...

322
00:15:15,440 --> 00:15:16,520
I was kinda mentally prepared.

323
00:15:16,560 --> 00:15:18,280
I was about to work on a new project

324
00:15:18,320 --> 00:15:22,520
and get to know new people.

325
00:15:22,560 --> 00:15:23,680
You're more than just someone new now.

326
00:15:23,720 --> 00:15:26,480
I got to learn more
about the plot and characters.

327
00:15:26,520 --> 00:15:29,080
On that day,
I was fairly prepared and excited.

328
00:15:29,320 --> 00:15:31,440
Again, I'm really glad to have met you.

329
00:15:32,460 --> 00:15:34,160
I just found out that she was prepared.

330
00:15:34,200 --> 00:15:35,400
On Day 1...

331
00:15:35,440 --> 00:15:37,000
I gave them an assignment.

332
00:15:37,040 --> 00:15:38,760
It was for them
to find ways to bond with each other.

333
00:15:38,800 --> 00:15:41,480
They could do whatever they wanted,
like going out together for a day.

334
00:15:41,800 --> 00:15:42,520
It was up to them.

335
00:15:42,560 --> 00:15:44,600
They had to get to know each other ASAP.

336
00:15:44,880 --> 00:15:48,080
So they went on a trip together
without telling anyone.

337
00:15:48,120 --> 00:15:50,800
I found out when they sent me their photos.

338
00:15:50,840 --> 00:15:53,400
I wanted to get to know her even better.

339
00:15:53,440 --> 00:15:56,760
I only got to know her through acting,

340
00:15:56,880 --> 00:16:00,280
and I didn't know
if that was really who she was.

341
00:16:00,440 --> 00:16:03,280
That's why I asked her to
go on a trip with me,

342
00:16:03,320 --> 00:16:05,720
just to go to a cafe
and have a meal together.

343
00:16:05,760 --> 00:16:08,000
And that's nice.

344
00:16:08,040 --> 00:16:10,880
I'm not sociable, you see.

345
00:16:10,920 --> 00:16:13,160
I don't socialize very often.
[Baipor isn't much of a talker]

346
00:16:13,200 --> 00:16:17,720
When it was time to break the ice,

347
00:16:17,760 --> 00:16:19,120
it was fairly challenging for me.

348
00:16:19,160 --> 00:16:23,270
But since we got to go on a trip
before the actual shoot,

349
00:16:23,310 --> 00:16:26,080
a lot of things became easier for me.

350
00:16:26,120 --> 00:16:29,460
I remember that when we were on a trip,

351
00:16:29,500 --> 00:16:31,000
I couldn't stop talking.

352
00:16:31,320 --> 00:16:34,840
We said we'd meet up at noon, right?

353
00:16:35,160 --> 00:16:36,880
From noon to 6 P.M.,

354
00:16:36,920 --> 00:16:39,280
- Mhm. I couldn't stop talking.
- she didn't stop talking

355
00:16:39,320 --> 00:16:41,560
until we went home.

356
00:16:41,600 --> 00:16:42,760
I felt really good that day

357
00:16:42,800 --> 00:16:47,120
because I felt like
I was able to be a good listener to her.

358
00:16:47,160 --> 00:16:48,720
Maybe?
[Of course you are!]

359
00:16:48,820 --> 00:16:52,440
If she's willing to
open up to me about something,

360
00:16:52,480 --> 00:16:54,790
it shows that she trusts me.

361
00:16:54,830 --> 00:17:00,050
That's why I felt that
we'd be very good partners for one another.

362
00:17:00,400 --> 00:17:05,720
Right, when it came to studying
our characters,

363
00:17:05,760 --> 00:17:10,200
- we went to workshops
- Mhm.

364
00:17:10,500 --> 00:17:13,319
- Yeah.
- to discover what they were like together.

365
00:17:13,520 --> 00:17:17,040
We were training with Instructor Sign
from SPARK Drama Studio.

366
00:17:17,079 --> 00:17:19,640
- It was a lot of fun, actually.
- It was.

367
00:17:19,680 --> 00:17:23,160
At first, we didn't get to play
our characters that much,

368
00:17:23,200 --> 00:17:25,560
- Mhm.
- but we got to break the ice

369
00:17:25,599 --> 00:17:28,060
- by playing scenes together.
- Yeah.

370
00:17:28,099 --> 00:17:31,520
I think it was also my first acting class.

371
00:17:31,560 --> 00:17:33,480
As for Baipor,
I'd say she's fairly experienced.

372
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:37,960
All I can say is that
I had a blast during the class.

373
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:39,440
Let's talk about the read-through.

374
00:17:39,480 --> 00:17:42,760
We did a read-through
and jumped straight into rehearsing.

375
00:17:43,300 --> 00:17:44,200
I wanted to see

376
00:17:44,240 --> 00:17:46,600
how they'd do as Jane and Z.

377
00:17:47,220 --> 00:17:48,720
We got together that day.

378
00:17:48,760 --> 00:17:50,240
They'd probably already done their training.

379
00:17:50,280 --> 00:17:53,200
One of their strengths is that
they train really hard.

380
00:17:53,240 --> 00:17:55,260
This helps them fully understand
the characters.

381
00:17:55,300 --> 00:17:57,080
So I got to meet Jane and Z, literally.
[She got to meet Jane and Z that day]

382
00:17:57,480 --> 00:17:58,480
That will do.

383
00:17:58,900 --> 00:18:00,000
Alright. Let's go.

384
00:18:01,040 --> 00:18:02,520
You're still mad at me?

385
00:18:02,870 --> 00:18:06,330
- Don't walk upstairs just yet.
- Down the stairs.

386
00:18:06,360 --> 00:18:08,760
Once the main characters were established,

387
00:18:08,860 --> 00:18:13,400
the plan was to have them meet
a bunch of other characters.

388
00:18:13,440 --> 00:18:16,720
This has been very deliberate
right from the start.

389
00:18:16,760 --> 00:18:19,440
It started with Jane and Z.

390
00:18:19,480 --> 00:18:21,440
We centered everything around them.

391
00:18:21,480 --> 00:18:24,160
We first established Jane's background.

392
00:18:24,200 --> 00:18:26,640
They would be a group of 3 fierce-looking people.
[Jane grew up with this LGBTQIA+ gang]

393
00:18:26,680 --> 00:18:28,960
One of them presents in a feminine fashion.

394
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:31,920
To put it simply, she's gay.

395
00:18:31,960 --> 00:18:34,600
Another member
is a woman with a fierce attitude.

396
00:18:34,900 --> 00:18:36,700
The group consists of Izzy, Natty, and Bushy.

397
00:18:36,720 --> 00:18:39,320
When it came to Z,
she needed supporting characters,

398
00:18:39,360 --> 00:18:40,880
Kaew-Ta and Duang-Jai.

399
00:18:40,920 --> 00:18:43,400
I could see Yam and Joke
playing the characters.

400
00:18:43,440 --> 00:18:48,840
I have several actor friends in the circle,

401
00:18:48,880 --> 00:18:52,760
such as Wan Thanakrit
and Joke from So Cool.

402
00:18:52,960 --> 00:18:55,360
Are you scared of ghosts?
[Let's enjoy some funny moments from Joke!]

403
00:18:55,520 --> 00:18:58,120
I've been scared of ghosts
since I was a boy.

404
00:18:59,120 --> 00:19:02,230
When I got married,
I became more scared of my wife than ghosts.

405
00:19:03,040 --> 00:19:05,240
A ghost or your wife, who would you choose?
[He's spitting out the truth!]

406
00:19:07,200 --> 00:19:08,720
My wife, of course!

407
00:19:08,840 --> 00:19:10,920
I wanna go back and see her so bad.
[I love my wife!]

408
00:19:11,560 --> 00:19:13,560
Between being jump-scared
by a ghost or your wife,

409
00:19:13,860 --> 00:19:14,860
which would you choose?

410
00:19:15,520 --> 00:19:16,640
A ghost, I'd say.

411
00:19:16,680 --> 00:19:18,960
I don't want
the person I love to scare me.

412
00:19:20,440 --> 00:19:22,000
This includes DJ Art as well.

413
00:19:22,040 --> 00:19:25,440
Everyone was down
to be a part of this series.

414
00:19:25,480 --> 00:19:28,360
We've also got actors from Fern,

415
00:19:28,950 --> 00:19:30,430
such as Pat.

416
00:19:30,470 --> 00:19:32,590
That's why it's such a lovely crew.

417
00:19:32,800 --> 00:19:34,790
We get to work with our closest ones,
[Working with friends who are professionals]

418
00:19:34,830 --> 00:19:37,550
friends and people we love,

419
00:19:37,590 --> 00:19:39,550
who are all talented

420
00:19:39,590 --> 00:19:43,030
and have distinct characters.

421
00:19:43,070 --> 00:19:46,150
They basically complete the series.

422
00:19:46,190 --> 00:19:49,870
The series references a theory.

423
00:19:49,910 --> 00:19:52,140
It's the six degrees of separation,

424
00:19:52,180 --> 00:19:53,760
or the small-world phenomenon.

425
00:19:53,800 --> 00:19:56,200
What if we use
the Six Degrees of Separation Theory

426
00:19:56,480 --> 00:19:58,640
or so-called the Small-World Phenomenon

427
00:19:58,680 --> 00:20:01,640
to find your old identity?

428
00:20:01,680 --> 00:20:03,720
Through people you used to know,

429
00:20:03,760 --> 00:20:05,640
people who heard you sing,

430
00:20:05,680 --> 00:20:08,640
or even through people
who might know who you were!!

431
00:20:08,680 --> 00:20:10,600
- Let's go!
- Let's go!!!

432
00:20:11,240 --> 00:20:12,640
Six Degrees, my a**.

433
00:20:12,680 --> 00:20:13,720
Delulu.

434
00:20:13,760 --> 00:20:16,640
The theory suggests that

435
00:20:16,680 --> 00:20:21,560
everyone is six or fewer
social connections away from one another.

436
00:20:22,740 --> 00:20:25,680
Eventually, we'll connect with
everyone all over the world.

437
00:20:25,720 --> 00:20:26,600
- Yeah.
- Mhm.

438
00:20:26,880 --> 00:20:29,760
The theory leads us to meet

439
00:20:29,800 --> 00:20:31,800
a bunch of other characters.
[The story leads us to countless characters]

440
00:20:31,840 --> 00:20:36,440
For example, Jin,
Jane's brother who is also a musician.

441
00:20:36,480 --> 00:20:38,240
And A-Mah, played by Taew.

442
00:20:38,600 --> 00:20:39,840
When it comes to Pat,

443
00:20:40,480 --> 00:20:43,120
Clare's character is someone who...

444
00:20:43,280 --> 00:20:46,700
- She totally owns the title 'Be My Angry!'
- Yes!

445
00:20:46,740 --> 00:20:50,240
She's very grumpy and moody.

446
00:20:50,280 --> 00:20:51,880
As for Tom,

447
00:20:51,920 --> 00:20:54,960
he's Jane's former boss.

448
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:57,200
She worked under him as an intern.

449
00:20:57,240 --> 00:21:01,680
He's one of the factors

450
00:21:02,520 --> 00:21:03,800
- that leads us to meet other characters.
- Yeah.

451
00:21:03,840 --> 00:21:04,890
He's a key factor.

452
00:21:04,930 --> 00:21:07,240
- Then there's Praew as Tuck.
- That's right.

453
00:21:07,280 --> 00:21:10,480
She's one of the secret characters.

454
00:21:10,520 --> 00:21:12,040
It's her.

455
00:21:12,080 --> 00:21:15,380
- She's Tom's older sister.
- Tom's.

456
00:21:15,420 --> 00:21:18,120
Another comedic character is...

457
00:21:18,160 --> 00:21:20,160
- Satanfah, a fortune teller
- Exactly.

458
00:21:20,200 --> 00:21:21,800
played by Gap.

459
00:21:21,840 --> 00:21:25,440
- He's also a key factor.
- Yeah.

460
00:21:25,480 --> 00:21:27,640
We've got a lot of
secret characters in the series.

461
00:21:27,680 --> 00:21:29,240
We also got to meet...

462
00:21:29,280 --> 00:21:30,400
Pai.

463
00:21:30,440 --> 00:21:32,800
- Played by DJ Art.
- That's right.

464
00:21:32,840 --> 00:21:37,670
I think we met him
in one of the first few scenes, right?

465
00:21:37,710 --> 00:21:39,800
- We met him on the first day.
- Yeah, the first day.

466
00:21:39,840 --> 00:21:43,320
I was delighted to meet him
on the first day.

467
00:21:43,360 --> 00:21:45,230
- It was one of the shooting days that...
- It was a lot of fun.

468
00:21:45,270 --> 00:21:47,330
- We had to hold in our laughter a lot.
- Yeah.

469
00:21:47,370 --> 00:21:48,880
I was really excited

470
00:21:48,920 --> 00:21:53,560
as the first day of the shoot was approaching.
[It was the first day of the shoot]

471
00:21:54,060 --> 00:21:56,340
I felt really good that the crew

472
00:21:56,380 --> 00:22:00,730
put DJ Art on the first day of the shoot.

473
00:22:00,880 --> 00:22:03,980
It really helped relieve a lot of my stress.

474
00:22:04,020 --> 00:22:06,220
The next person is Tony, right?

475
00:22:06,340 --> 00:22:08,920
He is played by Wan Thanakrit.

476
00:22:08,960 --> 00:22:13,520
Tony is also
one of the important characters

477
00:22:13,560 --> 00:22:17,560
- who hopes the two of us will...
- Yes.

478
00:22:17,600 --> 00:22:20,340
- So there's Wan and Joke,
- Yes.

479
00:22:20,380 --> 00:22:22,840
who we played scenes with.

480
00:22:22,880 --> 00:22:25,860
It was such an enjoyable shoot.

481
00:22:25,900 --> 00:22:28,140
- They already have great chemistry.
- Yeah.

482
00:22:28,180 --> 00:22:31,340
All we could do was sit there,
trying not to laugh.

483
00:22:32,020 --> 00:22:33,020
We pinched each other
to keep from laughing.

484
00:22:33,740 --> 00:22:34,500
It was so funny.

485
00:22:34,620 --> 00:22:35,480
Yeah.

486
00:22:35,520 --> 00:22:38,120
Another character is

487
00:22:38,160 --> 00:22:41,720
- Bew, played by Bo.
- Yes.

488
00:22:41,760 --> 00:22:46,140
- She's the owner of a painting studio.
- Yeah.

489
00:22:46,400 --> 00:22:49,540
I must say, this character...

490
00:22:50,080 --> 00:22:51,260
is a very important one.
[That's all she can tell us]

491
00:22:51,300 --> 00:22:52,560
She really is.

492
00:23:08,960 --> 00:23:10,800
I'd like to start with the overall concept.

493
00:23:10,920 --> 00:23:13,440
Because I wrote the script myself,

494
00:23:13,480 --> 00:23:17,500
I could clearly visualize it

495
00:23:17,540 --> 00:23:19,320
and break it down into details.

496
00:23:19,360 --> 00:23:21,800
We began with production design,

497
00:23:21,840 --> 00:23:25,140
discussing ideas with the team
[Production designing process]

498
00:23:25,150 --> 00:23:28,000
and consulting Fern

499
00:23:28,040 --> 00:23:29,800
about the visual direction.

500
00:23:29,840 --> 00:23:31,240
I wanted a surreal tone,

501
00:23:31,280 --> 00:23:33,560
but not so abstract that it's inaccessible.

502
00:23:33,760 --> 00:23:36,280
Using vivid colors

503
00:23:36,320 --> 00:23:41,600
and character-based props.

504
00:23:41,760 --> 00:23:44,920
The first step was choosing the main setting:

505
00:23:45,650 --> 00:23:46,840
Jane's house.

506
00:23:46,880 --> 00:23:48,560
I wanted a white house,

507
00:23:48,840 --> 00:23:52,280
so I could gradually fill it with colors

508
00:23:52,880 --> 00:23:57,400
and let the art direction team bring it to life.

509
00:23:57,440 --> 00:24:01,120
Jane is the most colorful character.

510
00:24:01,160 --> 00:24:06,000
Even the staircase walls
are filled with colorful images,

511
00:24:06,640 --> 00:24:09,600
so color is always present in every shot.

512
00:24:10,360 --> 00:24:17,640
Jane and Z's kitchen
is also designed to be full of color.

513
00:24:17,680 --> 00:24:21,280
In terms of character colors,

514
00:24:21,320 --> 00:24:23,560
Jane is yellow

515
00:24:23,600 --> 00:24:25,760
and Z is blue.

516
00:24:25,800 --> 00:24:28,520
Not literally throughout the entire series,

517
00:24:28,560 --> 00:24:31,040
but as a conceptual guide.
[Identity colors]

518
00:24:31,200 --> 00:24:33,720
One represents daytime,
and the other represents nighttime.

519
00:24:33,760 --> 00:24:36,160
Warm, daylight energy.

520
00:24:36,400 --> 00:24:37,120
Something like that.

521
00:24:37,160 --> 00:24:40,120
This concept was then passed on
to the art and costume teams.

522
00:24:40,160 --> 00:24:42,840
After finishing the mock location viewing,
[Patcharapol Jantaramanit, Art Director]

523
00:24:42,880 --> 00:24:45,680
we moved on to pitching the key visual.

524
00:24:46,240 --> 00:24:49,080
I kept discussing with Poy,

525
00:24:49,120 --> 00:24:51,000
exchanging ideas

526
00:24:51,400 --> 00:24:53,960
and adjusting what needed to be added.

527
00:24:54,160 --> 00:24:59,560
For the color palette,
we used sapphic colors.

528
00:24:59,800 --> 00:25:02,500
Poy set the main tones as

529
00:25:03,160 --> 00:25:07,460
purple, yellow, pink, and white.

530
00:25:07,840 --> 00:25:10,280
These became the core colors of the series.

531
00:25:10,760 --> 00:25:14,940
If you look closely at the house,
it's very clear that

532
00:25:15,320 --> 00:25:17,000
only these colors are used.

533
00:25:17,040 --> 00:25:20,320
In the bedroom, we used yellow curtains.

534
00:25:20,360 --> 00:25:23,120
The space I wanted to highlight most
is Jane's bedroom in EP1.

535
00:25:23,160 --> 00:25:26,000
Before Z enters her life,

536
00:25:26,040 --> 00:25:30,000
Jane usually leaves her clothes
hanging around

537
00:25:30,040 --> 00:25:32,400
with underwear scattered everywhere.

538
00:25:32,440 --> 00:25:33,880
She lives alone, you know.

539
00:25:33,920 --> 00:25:35,000
We went all in.

540
00:25:35,200 --> 00:25:37,320
It clearly shows
what kind of person Jane is.

541
00:25:37,360 --> 00:25:38,680
As for the infused liquor bar,

542
00:25:38,720 --> 00:25:41,160
when people think of it,
they usually imagine a shack.

543
00:25:41,200 --> 00:25:43,880
But we wanted it to be an actual shop,

544
00:25:43,920 --> 00:25:46,720
so we chose a cafe instead.

545
00:25:46,760 --> 00:25:50,680
Originally, it was just a cafe,

546
00:25:50,720 --> 00:25:53,200
and we redesigned it
into an infused liquor bar.

547
00:25:53,800 --> 00:25:58,840
We turned a chic cafe into a bar

548
00:25:58,880 --> 00:26:01,760
with fun and weird vibes.
[Added more vibes to it]

549
00:26:01,800 --> 00:26:03,520
I was having so much fun.

550
00:26:03,560 --> 00:26:08,120
Poy didn't fix any strict rules.

551
00:26:08,160 --> 00:26:13,440
We were free
to be as creative as we wanted.

552
00:26:13,480 --> 00:26:16,080
We added colorful LED lights.

553
00:26:16,240 --> 00:26:19,480
More color, more fun.

554
00:26:19,520 --> 00:26:22,040
We mixed in everything
that intentionally felt mismatched.

555
00:26:22,080 --> 00:26:23,360
Out of nowhere, there are Lanna flags.

556
00:26:23,400 --> 00:26:25,520
Out of nowhere,
there are these weird-looking dolls.

557
00:26:25,560 --> 00:26:27,680
The goal was to decorate it
to be as playful as possible.

558
00:26:27,720 --> 00:26:32,400
Even the infused liquor names
were newly created.

559
00:26:32,640 --> 00:26:34,200
Something like,

560
00:26:34,240 --> 00:26:35,880
"Unicorn Gone Wild."

561
00:26:35,920 --> 00:26:38,440
The whole setting process
was really enjoyable.

562
00:26:38,480 --> 00:26:43,120
For the props,
we packed in as much detail as possible

563
00:26:43,160 --> 00:26:45,640
to tell the characters' stories.

564
00:26:45,880 --> 00:26:48,520
The brief came from Poy,
and it was already very solid.

565
00:26:48,560 --> 00:26:52,000
I knew it was fantasy-driven
the moment she told us.

566
00:26:52,040 --> 00:26:55,040
Her script was detailed from the start.

567
00:26:55,360 --> 00:26:57,990
Our job was simply to add more color to it.

568
00:26:58,030 --> 00:26:59,880
The costume concept also came from Poy.

569
00:26:59,920 --> 00:27:02,520
- She wanted the costumes...
- Right, she wanted...

570
00:27:02,820 --> 00:27:05,400
Bambam's character
to change outfits every single day.

571
00:27:05,440 --> 00:27:06,880
- There's a reason, though.
- Yeah, every day.

572
00:27:07,080 --> 00:27:09,680
It was actually a bug.

573
00:27:09,720 --> 00:27:12,480
This angel once existed in the real world,

574
00:27:12,520 --> 00:27:15,880
so now that she's working for Jane,

575
00:27:15,920 --> 00:27:19,600
we don't want people
from her past to recognize her.

576
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:22,240
Poy then said the bug had been fixed

577
00:27:22,340 --> 00:27:23,520
by changing outfits.

578
00:27:23,790 --> 00:27:25,520
Outfits that confuse people.

579
00:27:25,990 --> 00:27:27,400
[This one confused me, too]

580
00:27:30,680 --> 00:27:32,440
- Hold that for her.
- Let me hold it.

581
00:27:32,960 --> 00:27:35,120
- Watch your step.
- Be careful.

582
00:27:37,320 --> 00:27:40,160
Moving on to the costume design,

583
00:27:40,200 --> 00:27:43,280
there'd be normal outfits and fantasy ones

584
00:27:43,320 --> 00:27:46,120
because the rule is...

585
00:27:46,160 --> 00:27:48,840
people in the series would see Z
in different looks.

586
00:27:48,880 --> 00:27:50,840
It's fun to...

587
00:27:51,120 --> 00:27:54,680
As a screenwriter and a director,

588
00:27:54,920 --> 00:27:56,360
it's fun to go all out.

589
00:27:56,400 --> 00:27:59,810
But I need to ask the costume team
if they had fun, too.

590
00:27:59,850 --> 00:28:01,320
I was kinda surprised.

591
00:28:01,360 --> 00:28:02,720
[Wanlapa Tangmitcharoen, Costume Designer]

592
00:28:02,760 --> 00:28:05,880
It didn't seem hard when I read the script,

593
00:28:05,920 --> 00:28:08,400
but once I started
working on the demo outfits,

594
00:28:08,440 --> 00:28:10,800
I had to check how many outfits were needed.

595
00:28:10,840 --> 00:28:12,320
And that's when it surprised me

596
00:28:14,240 --> 00:28:15,600
that there were so many.

597
00:28:15,840 --> 00:28:18,000
We're truly sorry.

598
00:28:19,360 --> 00:28:21,800
I think she might not be very happy, but...

599
00:28:23,120 --> 00:28:25,160
- We're lucky
- I'll let Poy

600
00:28:25,340 --> 00:28:26,500
- that we can avoid her.
- handle that.

601
00:28:26,540 --> 00:28:27,280
Right.

602
00:28:28,700 --> 00:28:30,480
Fewer outfits would be nice.

603
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:32,940
I feel bad for Bambam
that she had to change a lot.

604
00:28:32,980 --> 00:28:34,920
She even had to wear a wig and a mustache.

605
00:28:34,960 --> 00:28:36,040
An ancient cinnamon roll.

606
00:28:36,080 --> 00:28:37,860
She had to dress
like a man from ancient times,

607
00:28:37,900 --> 00:28:39,720
and I wanted to go all out.

608
00:28:39,760 --> 00:28:41,240
I already asked her

609
00:28:41,280 --> 00:28:43,120
if she was okay, though.
[The ancient cinnamon roll]

610
00:28:43,160 --> 00:28:45,960
Was I forced to be like that?

611
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:47,460
I was actually being myself.

612
00:28:47,680 --> 00:28:49,360
It just felt tiring sometimes
when I had to change the outfits.

613
00:28:49,550 --> 00:28:52,920
I'd have so many looks.

614
00:28:53,460 --> 00:28:54,840
- In this series...
- Which one did you like the most?

615
00:28:55,200 --> 00:28:56,440
Which one?

616
00:28:56,800 --> 00:28:58,840
I liked the lobster one.

617
00:28:59,570 --> 00:29:00,880
I like it, though.

618
00:29:00,920 --> 00:29:02,960
I was really having fun.

619
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:04,160
- There was one outfit...
- Okay.

620
00:29:04,200 --> 00:29:05,640
The spacesuit.

621
00:29:05,680 --> 00:29:09,240
It was so heavy and hot.
I had a hard time trying to breathe in there.

622
00:29:09,280 --> 00:29:13,360
Anyway, I was happy
with every outfit I got to wear

623
00:29:13,400 --> 00:29:17,360
'cause it made everyone laugh,
and that was enough.

624
00:29:17,400 --> 00:29:22,320
Amazing work, guys.
I'm really happy I got to do it.

625
00:29:22,480 --> 00:29:28,320
And Jane's style is very Gen Z and modern,

626
00:29:28,360 --> 00:29:32,400
so we tried to add small details.

627
00:29:32,440 --> 00:29:36,280
Jane's look should feel fun and cute,

628
00:29:36,320 --> 00:29:40,320
so we added nail art stickers

629
00:29:40,360 --> 00:29:44,800
to make her style playful and colorful.

630
00:29:44,840 --> 00:29:47,840
Her nails would change designs every day.

631
00:29:47,880 --> 00:29:52,560
All of them were
bright, detailed, and trendy,

632
00:29:52,600 --> 00:29:57,520
with shapes and textures that reflect Jane.

633
00:29:57,560 --> 00:30:01,120
Sometimes the stickers
fell off and went missing,

634
00:30:01,160 --> 00:30:04,840
but Fern always found them.

635
00:30:04,880 --> 00:30:06,360
Aren't you lowkey curious

636
00:30:06,400 --> 00:30:08,960
why people end up seeing you
in different kinds of looks?

637
00:30:09,120 --> 00:30:10,160
Why then?

638
00:30:10,200 --> 00:30:13,040
That heavy wolf cut was so last decade, kids.

639
00:30:13,080 --> 00:30:13,840
- Sh*t!
- Sh*t!!

640
00:30:14,800 --> 00:30:17,760
Once the production design was set,

641
00:30:17,800 --> 00:30:20,680
we worked on visuals and editing.

642
00:30:20,880 --> 00:30:24,160
For the visuals,
we worked closely with the DP, Poom.

643
00:30:24,200 --> 00:30:30,840
I told him I wanted to show something
rarely seen in other sapphic series.

644
00:30:30,880 --> 00:30:32,360
Poy's first brief was that
[Tanakorn Krailassuwan,]

645
00:30:32,400 --> 00:30:35,520
she wanted the series to feel different.
[Director of Photography]

646
00:30:35,560 --> 00:30:37,800
Unique in color, lighting, and camera work.

647
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:39,560
She wanted it to feel more like a film.

648
00:30:39,600 --> 00:30:40,840
Since it's fantasy

649
00:30:40,880 --> 00:30:44,760
and we aimed for a surreal world,

650
00:30:44,800 --> 00:30:48,120
we explored creative angles.
[Building the world with new angles]

651
00:30:48,160 --> 00:30:51,120
Like using distortion shots,

652
00:30:51,160 --> 00:30:54,000
wide lenses close to the characters,

653
00:30:54,800 --> 00:30:59,240
or framing two people talking
in unconventional ways.

654
00:30:59,600 --> 00:31:02,720
Sometimes we used overhead shots,

655
00:31:02,760 --> 00:31:05,800
pressing down
to make characters feel oppressed.

656
00:31:05,920 --> 00:31:09,160
But every design choice had to remain
within the cinematic language.

657
00:31:09,440 --> 00:31:11,680
For this series, 'Be My Angel,'

658
00:31:11,720 --> 00:31:15,720
I picked a frame ratio
that's not like other series.

659
00:31:15,760 --> 00:31:21,120
Internationally, they use 2.20:1

660
00:31:21,160 --> 00:31:24,620
for TV shows,
[2.20:1 for a series]

661
00:31:24,660 --> 00:31:26,920
which still feels somewhat cinematic.

662
00:31:26,960 --> 00:31:28,200
During the fitting,

663
00:31:28,520 --> 00:31:33,360
I tested the framing with Baipor

664
00:31:33,880 --> 00:31:35,400
to see how a full-body shot would look

665
00:31:35,440 --> 00:31:37,920
and how it'd change
in dark or bright light.

666
00:31:37,960 --> 00:31:39,120
I compared three sizes

667
00:31:39,160 --> 00:31:42,760
to see how each would feel on a device.

668
00:31:43,160 --> 00:31:46,480
For the shot designing,
we used storyboards.

669
00:31:46,520 --> 00:31:49,120
We started by blocking the shots first.

670
00:31:49,160 --> 00:31:51,120
Then we arranged all the blocked shots

671
00:31:51,160 --> 00:31:55,120
to plan the scenes for the day.

672
00:31:55,160 --> 00:31:58,000
From there, we developed
the storyboard based on that design.

673
00:31:58,160 --> 00:32:00,020
During filming,
Poy would come over and say,

674
00:32:00,060 --> 00:32:01,860
"Hey, I want this shot, too.
Can you do it for me?"

675
00:32:01,900 --> 00:32:05,180
Sometimes I had already designed
10-12 shots,

676
00:32:05,220 --> 00:32:07,380
and she would add more,
bringing it up to 15.

677
00:32:07,680 --> 00:32:09,680
I'm all about improvising.

678
00:32:09,920 --> 00:32:11,520
I always wanted more.

679
00:32:11,560 --> 00:32:14,000
"Hey, I want this, too."

680
00:32:14,300 --> 00:32:17,560
"Can you do this, too?"

681
00:32:17,600 --> 00:32:19,360
And he could make it happen for me.

682
00:32:19,400 --> 00:32:21,720
One shot design I want to share

683
00:32:21,880 --> 00:32:26,400
is the laundromat scene.

684
00:32:26,440 --> 00:32:28,960
It was designed together
with the screenwriters.

685
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:30,920
It's probably the most detailed scene
in the series.

686
00:32:30,960 --> 00:32:33,080
It's a laundromat scene

687
00:32:33,120 --> 00:32:35,400
with a small love scene.

688
00:32:35,600 --> 00:32:38,720
When the characters looked at each other,
everything stopped.

689
00:32:38,760 --> 00:32:40,600
It was just them.

690
00:32:40,640 --> 00:32:42,080
The spinning clothes stopped spinning.

691
00:32:43,080 --> 00:32:44,840
The dripping water stopped dripping.

692
00:32:44,880 --> 00:32:46,040
I told Poom that.

693
00:32:46,080 --> 00:32:47,560
I had to ask the CG team,

694
00:32:47,600 --> 00:32:50,000
deciding on pacing, number of layers,

695
00:32:50,040 --> 00:32:51,240
and speed.

696
00:32:51,280 --> 00:32:55,560
The tricky part was
the dryers only ran for a set amount of time.

697
00:32:55,940 --> 00:32:58,480
Each spin gave a very short window,

698
00:32:58,520 --> 00:32:59,920
so we had to move fast.

699
00:33:00,180 --> 00:33:02,840
And we only had 2-3 more spins left.
[Working against the clock]

700
00:33:02,880 --> 00:33:04,080
It was challenging.

701
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:06,060
Always.

702
00:33:06,240 --> 00:33:08,000
Every time.
[#SavePoom]

703
00:33:08,240 --> 00:33:11,120
I have to apologize to the team
for all the extra work.

704
00:33:11,160 --> 00:33:16,640
The CG team, assistant directors,
DP, and editors...

705
00:33:16,680 --> 00:33:19,360
We even had meetings
just for this one scene.

706
00:33:19,600 --> 00:33:21,440
But in the end, we did it.

707
00:33:21,480 --> 00:33:23,560
Thanks to everyone
for making the vision come true.

708
00:33:23,600 --> 00:33:24,760
It's exactly what I wanted.

709
00:33:24,800 --> 00:33:26,960
Turning a simple scene
into something interesting.

710
00:33:36,080 --> 00:33:41,460
Another key location in the series
is Song Wat Road.

711
00:33:41,500 --> 00:33:42,900
It's an open area.

712
00:33:43,280 --> 00:33:44,180
We didn't close the road.

713
00:33:44,220 --> 00:33:49,440
On the filming day,
there were some people around.

714
00:33:49,480 --> 00:33:51,620
We didn't block anyone

715
00:33:51,750 --> 00:33:52,840
and just kept going.

716
00:33:52,880 --> 00:33:56,770
Shooting at Song Wat
was another big day for us.

717
00:33:56,810 --> 00:33:58,040
Yeah, it was.

718
00:33:58,080 --> 00:34:01,720
It represents Bangkok

719
00:34:01,760 --> 00:34:05,320
and modern Thailand pretty well.

720
00:34:05,360 --> 00:34:11,800
It's a well-known landmark
that tourists often visit.

721
00:34:11,840 --> 00:34:13,639
- We were so fortunate
- It's popular.

722
00:34:13,679 --> 00:34:18,199
to have this location in our series.

723
00:34:18,239 --> 00:34:19,960
- Like...
- It's a Gen Z hotspot.

724
00:34:20,000 --> 00:34:21,679
Yeah, it is.

725
00:34:21,719 --> 00:34:25,239
It fits our storyline

726
00:34:25,280 --> 00:34:26,800
- Right.
- and setting.

727
00:34:27,070 --> 00:34:29,480
And Song Wat is visually stunning.

728
00:34:29,520 --> 00:34:30,639
The walls...

729
00:34:30,679 --> 00:34:32,199
That scene felt very organic.

730
00:34:32,239 --> 00:34:36,360
There were a lot of crew members,

731
00:34:36,400 --> 00:34:40,080
and the rest were actual tourists.

732
00:34:40,120 --> 00:34:43,960
We made sure to get their consent
before filming, though.

733
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:46,719
We had a lot of scenes to shoot,

734
00:34:46,760 --> 00:34:50,679
but we had limited time
during the day.

735
00:34:51,080 --> 00:34:53,139
I really want to give credit to the team.

736
00:34:53,179 --> 00:34:56,679
Without great set management,

737
00:34:56,719 --> 00:34:59,320
a good line producer,
and skilled assistant directors,

738
00:34:59,360 --> 00:35:00,960
we wouldn't have pulled it off.

739
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:02,320
As for Song Wat...

740
00:35:02,360 --> 00:35:05,200
When I scouted the location,

741
00:35:05,320 --> 00:35:07,800
I thought it'd be a small setup.

742
00:35:07,840 --> 00:35:11,800
But when I saw the set,

743
00:35:11,840 --> 00:35:13,000
it was actually quite large.

744
00:35:13,040 --> 00:35:15,960
That day on Song Wat Road was something.

745
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:17,520
The weather was hot.

746
00:35:17,560 --> 00:35:21,320
The location was far and crowded.

747
00:35:21,360 --> 00:35:24,360
There were many outfits
the actresses had to wear,

748
00:35:24,400 --> 00:35:26,240
so I decided
to just bring the whole rack.

749
00:35:26,280 --> 00:35:28,840
There were accessories,
nail stickers, and so many more.

750
00:35:28,880 --> 00:35:30,560
So I just brought them all.

751
00:35:30,600 --> 00:35:36,360
Costume changes were tricky
with so many people around.

752
00:35:36,400 --> 00:35:38,560
They had to change discreetly.

753
00:35:38,600 --> 00:35:42,000
And with limited time,
we had to hurry, too.

754
00:35:42,040 --> 00:35:46,760
There was a tent and a clothing rack
for the actresses to use.

755
00:35:47,120 --> 00:35:50,240
We'd set up the tent

756
00:35:51,120 --> 00:35:52,840
and have the actresses change in there.

757
00:35:53,240 --> 00:35:56,180
There was one chaotic moment

758
00:35:56,220 --> 00:35:59,380
when one was changing
while the other was putting on nail stickers.

759
00:35:59,720 --> 00:36:02,080
Before we went to Song Wat,

760
00:36:02,120 --> 00:36:04,360
our plan was to keep it simple
and eventually add more details.

761
00:36:04,880 --> 00:36:07,940
However, it didn't go as planned.

762
00:36:07,980 --> 00:36:09,840
We just...

763
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:13,120
took everything we could find.
[Let's do our best!]

764
00:36:13,160 --> 00:36:15,860
The camera and lighting teams
deserve praise.

765
00:36:16,160 --> 00:36:20,300
The lighting department split into zones

766
00:36:20,340 --> 00:36:21,720
and supported each other.

767
00:36:21,760 --> 00:36:25,440
The camera team deserves full credit.

768
00:36:25,680 --> 00:36:28,920
When given instructions,
they acted immediately.

769
00:36:29,470 --> 00:36:31,910
Without them, it wouldn't have worked.

770
00:36:32,400 --> 00:36:34,680
It was a mix of fun and challenges.

771
00:36:34,720 --> 00:36:36,440
- There were challenges.
- Yeah, right.

772
00:36:36,480 --> 00:36:38,040
- Yeah.
- One of them was...

773
00:36:38,440 --> 00:36:39,800
It was sunny,

774
00:36:39,840 --> 00:36:42,560
- but suddenly, it got cloudy.
- Exactly.

775
00:36:42,680 --> 00:36:45,240
Another crucial team on set was

776
00:36:45,280 --> 00:36:49,520
the "Divine Relations" team,
aka the Ministry of Magic.

777
00:36:50,100 --> 00:36:52,880
I had no idea this existed.
[They help chase the rain away]

778
00:36:52,920 --> 00:36:54,840
They told me it's very important

779
00:36:54,880 --> 00:36:56,760
to have them on every set.

780
00:36:57,040 --> 00:37:00,400
- And...
- Every time it got cloudy,

781
00:37:00,440 --> 00:37:03,440
they'd do their job
[Pon, one of the team]

782
00:37:03,800 --> 00:37:05,160
by praying,

783
00:37:05,680 --> 00:37:07,120
and it actually worked!

784
00:37:07,160 --> 00:37:09,320
- That really amazed me.
- Right.

785
00:37:09,400 --> 00:37:10,500
The sky became clear

786
00:37:10,540 --> 00:37:12,740
- because...
- The Ministry of Magic stepped in.

787
00:37:12,780 --> 00:37:14,580
- Exactly, and they did well.
- They did an amazing job.

788
00:37:14,960 --> 00:37:17,040
[When I fall in love...

789
00:37:17,080 --> 00:37:18,680
with my angel...]

790
00:37:21,440 --> 00:37:22,320
How was it?

791
00:37:22,800 --> 00:37:23,800
Can you recall anything now?

792
00:37:38,820 --> 00:37:41,280
Got it, having a girlfriend is this good.

793
00:37:47,560 --> 00:37:50,040
From the start,

794
00:37:50,080 --> 00:37:52,000
we wanted a lovely scene.

795
00:37:52,280 --> 00:37:55,360
Simple yet special.

796
00:37:55,600 --> 00:38:00,720
Like the scene where they sat
before each other and said,

797
00:38:00,940 --> 00:38:02,860
"Can you recall anything now?"

798
00:38:02,900 --> 00:38:06,080
I wanted that scene in my series.

799
00:38:06,120 --> 00:38:07,480
That's it, simple.

800
00:38:07,520 --> 00:38:09,200
But it's cute.

801
00:38:09,240 --> 00:38:12,200
I want something
that'd make viewers recall

802
00:38:12,240 --> 00:38:14,280
something they've done with their partner.
[Cute, relatable scenes]

803
00:38:14,320 --> 00:38:16,800
I want them to think of those moments

804
00:38:16,840 --> 00:38:20,160
and miss them again.

805
00:38:20,200 --> 00:38:23,660
This scene was based on my true story, too.

806
00:38:23,800 --> 00:38:26,860
I mean, I don't know why,

807
00:38:27,220 --> 00:38:28,980
but my wife always wants me
to scratch her back.

808
00:38:29,020 --> 00:38:30,700
I think it's cute,

809
00:38:30,740 --> 00:38:32,720
so I added it into the series.

810
00:38:32,760 --> 00:38:36,460
I loved the cute scenes, though.

811
00:38:36,500 --> 00:38:38,260
- Which one?
- I like...

812
00:38:38,500 --> 00:38:42,380
simple, everyday moments

813
00:38:42,420 --> 00:38:47,560
that carry the story's
most important emotions.

814
00:38:47,600 --> 00:38:50,440
The story is told through everyday life,

815
00:38:50,480 --> 00:38:52,880
but these simple moments
are the ones that are truly special.

816
00:38:52,920 --> 00:38:54,240
Simple yet extraordinary.

817
00:38:54,280 --> 00:38:55,300
Sometimes it's like...

818
00:38:55,340 --> 00:38:56,960
She'll be upset after that.

819
00:38:57,000 --> 00:38:59,240
- One of them might not be in the mood.
- Exactly.

820
00:38:59,280 --> 00:39:01,160
But it's cute anyway.

821
00:39:01,200 --> 00:39:02,110
- I know that.
- Well,

822
00:39:02,240 --> 00:39:03,680
it's very common for couples.

823
00:39:03,880 --> 00:39:06,120
Even if they were happy a moment ago,

824
00:39:06,160 --> 00:39:08,360
they could end up fighting. It's normal.
[So your life's fun]

825
00:39:08,400 --> 00:39:09,480
It was pretty real.

826
00:39:09,520 --> 00:39:12,160
Most of the time,
Baipor would encourage Bambam more.

827
00:39:12,580 --> 00:39:15,240
Like that scene in the trailer where...

828
00:39:15,280 --> 00:39:19,080
they sat in front of each other, saying,

829
00:39:19,380 --> 00:39:20,880
"Can you recall anything now?"

830
00:39:20,920 --> 00:39:23,320
Bambam was blushing so hard

831
00:39:24,080 --> 00:39:25,480
that she couldn't look at Baipor,

832
00:39:25,520 --> 00:39:29,000
so Baipor told her, "It's okay.

833
00:39:29,480 --> 00:39:31,960
Let's say it's just us here.

834
00:39:32,320 --> 00:39:33,680
Don't care about anyone.

835
00:39:33,960 --> 00:39:35,160
Look at me.

836
00:39:35,200 --> 00:39:36,720
Can you be with me?"

837
00:39:37,120 --> 00:39:39,320
That's what I saw,

838
00:39:39,600 --> 00:39:40,880
and I think it was cute.

839
00:39:41,360 --> 00:39:44,800
They also had to run on a mission

840
00:39:45,100 --> 00:39:46,260
to get tired together.

841
00:39:46,620 --> 00:39:48,480
They were cheering each other up.

842
00:39:48,800 --> 00:39:52,520
And there aren't
any intense love scenes in this series.

843
00:39:52,560 --> 00:39:55,960
Just hand-holding
and kisses on the cheek.

844
00:39:56,000 --> 00:39:58,840
And they'd count
how many times they kissed each day,

845
00:39:59,200 --> 00:40:00,600
which is super cute.

846
00:40:00,640 --> 00:40:03,860
Regardless of gender,

847
00:40:04,640 --> 00:40:09,280
it's all about love and feelings.

848
00:40:09,320 --> 00:40:13,300
Although it's a fantasy series,

849
00:40:13,340 --> 00:40:17,680
surreal and unrealistic,

850
00:40:17,720 --> 00:40:20,920
it'd actually feel nice to have an angel

851
00:40:20,960 --> 00:40:23,760
that could give you everything.

852
00:40:23,800 --> 00:40:26,520
All of your wishes will be granted.

853
00:40:26,560 --> 00:40:28,480
And the plot twist is that

854
00:40:28,520 --> 00:40:31,960
this angel can't grant anything.

855
00:40:32,000 --> 00:40:36,360
However, one thing that they'll get
from this relationship

856
00:40:36,400 --> 00:40:39,520
is the love they share.
[Love is for everyone]

857
00:40:39,560 --> 00:40:41,600
And I think it's universal.

858
00:40:41,640 --> 00:40:44,160
Regardless of gender,

859
00:40:44,200 --> 00:40:49,320
this will touch your heart as a person.

860
00:40:49,360 --> 00:40:55,720
And that's why I think
this series can make you happy.

861
00:40:55,760 --> 00:40:58,040
The actresses are very sweet.

862
00:40:58,200 --> 00:40:59,480
I want people to feel our dedication.

863
00:40:59,520 --> 00:41:04,190
Whether it was the camera team,
the lighting team, or the assistants,

864
00:41:04,230 --> 00:41:08,560
every team gave their full effort
and supported one another throughout.

865
00:41:08,780 --> 00:41:10,320
We had so much fun.

866
00:41:10,360 --> 00:41:12,800
Their acting was...

867
00:41:13,880 --> 00:41:15,800
enjoyable. Every one of them.

868
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:19,640
Everyone was funny.

869
00:41:19,740 --> 00:41:21,800
I want you to check it out.

870
00:41:21,840 --> 00:41:23,880
All the settings...

871
00:41:25,080 --> 00:41:27,240
were done with heart.

872
00:41:27,920 --> 00:41:31,120
We tried to add all the details,
like colors,

873
00:41:31,440 --> 00:41:34,120
the fun,

874
00:41:34,160 --> 00:41:36,160
and fantasy vibes, into it.

875
00:41:36,200 --> 00:41:39,320
Please look forward to...

876
00:41:39,360 --> 00:41:42,720
tons of fancy outfits.

877
00:41:43,280 --> 00:41:44,280
Please stay tuned.

878
00:41:44,480 --> 00:41:47,640
Poy's a butch, which makes her
one of the most insightful directors for this.

879
00:41:47,680 --> 00:41:51,320
And one of the screenwriters is Bear,
who's also a butch.

880
00:41:51,360 --> 00:41:59,440
It's the realest butch-femme story for me.

881
00:41:59,480 --> 00:42:02,320
I'm part of the butch-femme community,

882
00:42:02,360 --> 00:42:05,000
and Poy and I are married.

883
00:42:05,040 --> 00:42:08,000
Today is an era beyond gender.

884
00:42:08,040 --> 00:42:10,680
We tried to go beyond gender

885
00:42:10,720 --> 00:42:14,240
and make everything feel normal.

886
00:42:14,280 --> 00:42:20,720
So I think you'll definitely enjoy this series.

887
00:42:20,760 --> 00:42:24,200
Please look forward to 'Be My Angel.'

888
00:42:24,240 --> 00:42:26,360
Personally, I think it's my masterpiece.

889
00:42:26,400 --> 00:42:28,790
I poured my heart
into writing and making it.

890
00:42:29,520 --> 00:42:34,440
To me, it's like a strawberry
with dark chocolate inside.

891
00:42:35,240 --> 00:42:41,460
Sweet and bright on the outside,

892
00:42:41,720 --> 00:42:44,560
bitter when you bite into it,

893
00:42:44,800 --> 00:42:48,240
but delicious when it comes together.

894
00:42:49,680 --> 00:42:51,080
That's what this series is.

895
00:42:51,480 --> 00:42:54,200
It's a romantic comedy with fantasy...

896
00:42:54,240 --> 00:42:57,280
and drama, feel-good and heartwarming.

897
00:42:57,600 --> 00:42:59,440
Please give it a chance.

898
00:42:59,480 --> 00:43:01,320
It may feel new,

899
00:43:01,540 --> 00:43:04,320
but if you keep an open mind,

900
00:43:04,560 --> 00:43:07,080
you'll love it as much as we do.

901
00:43:07,120 --> 00:43:08,720
From everything we've said,

902
00:43:08,760 --> 00:43:11,840
I think you can already tell

903
00:43:12,400 --> 00:43:16,400
- How fun it'll be.
- how fun this series will be.

904
00:43:16,440 --> 00:43:18,720
It explores many themes,

905
00:43:18,760 --> 00:43:21,320
including family,

906
00:43:21,360 --> 00:43:23,880
relatives,

907
00:43:23,920 --> 00:43:27,120
and diverse types of relationships.

908
00:43:27,160 --> 00:43:33,800
The key focus is the relationship
between Jane and Z,

909
00:43:33,840 --> 00:43:38,040
portrayed through a butch-femme dynamic.

910
00:43:38,080 --> 00:43:42,480
The story feels modern,

911
00:43:42,520 --> 00:43:46,280
with a clear setting and many details,

912
00:43:46,320 --> 00:43:50,330
- blending different cultural elements.
- Right.

913
00:43:50,680 --> 00:43:57,080
Z may be the more masculine one
in the relationship,

914
00:43:57,120 --> 00:43:58,880
but in the series,

915
00:43:59,020 --> 00:44:01,160
Jane's a better leader.

916
00:44:01,400 --> 00:44:02,440
It's like that.

917
00:44:02,480 --> 00:44:06,020
It's not that only Z can protect Jane.
[Protect each other]

918
00:44:06,170 --> 00:44:07,790
Jane can protect her, too.

919
00:44:07,830 --> 00:44:12,960
I want people to see
many perspectives on that.

920
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:15,120
Please look forward to...

921
00:44:15,160 --> 00:44:17,080
- 'Be My Angel.'
- 'Be My Angel.'

922
00:44:17,120 --> 00:44:19,640
- I fell in love...
- With my angel!
